<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>
  
<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-1">
  <title>Meaning of a Vector</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      An expression like 
      <m>\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix}</m>
      represents:
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>A point or vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. An <m>n</m>-tuple as a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A single real number.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this notation represents multiple components.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A 2‑dimensional point only.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—it generalizes to any dimension.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-2">
  <title>Adding Vectors</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let  
      <m>\vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}</m>  
      and  
      <m>\vec{v}=\begin{bmatrix}4\\0\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
      Compute <m>\vec{u}+\vec{v}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}5\\2\\2\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Vectors are added component‑wise.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}5\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect third component.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\\4\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this is not componentwise addition.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-3">
  <title>Scalar Multiplication</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute <m>3\vec{w}</m> where  
      <m>\vec{w}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\-1\\4\end{bmatrix}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}6\\-3\\12\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Multiply each component by the scalar.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3\\-1\\4\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Only the first component was scaled.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}6\\2\\8\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect scaling of the second and third components.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-4">
  <title>Definition of a Linear Mapping</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      A mapping <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n\to\mathbb{R}^m</m> is linear if:
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>T(\vec{u}+\vec{v}) = T(\vec{u}) + T(\vec{v})</m>  
          and  
          <m>T(c\vec{u}) = c\,T(\vec{u})</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This is the definition of linearity.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p>T must preserve vector lengths.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—only orthogonal mappings do that.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p>T must output a scalar.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—it outputs vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-5">
  <title>Columns of a Matrix</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For a linear mapping <m>T(\vec{x})=A\vec{x}</m>, what does each column of <m>A</m> represent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The vector <m>T(\vec{e}_i)</m>, the image of the <m>i</m>-th standard basis vector.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Columns of <m>A</m> are <m>T(\vec{e}_1),\dots,T(\vec{e}_n)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p>The eigenvalues of <m>A</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—eigenvalues are not arranged as columns.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p>Randomly chosen vectors.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—each column encodes <m>T</m> fully.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-6">
  <title>Matrix–Vector Multiplication</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let  
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2\\3 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>  
      and  
      <m>\vec{x}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\4\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
      Compute <m>A\vec{x}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}9\\7\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct:  
          <m>1\cdot 1 + 2\cdot 4 = 9</m>,  
          <m>3\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 4 = 7</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3\\4\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—these are row sums, not <m>A\vec{x}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\4\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that is just <m>\vec{x}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-7">
  <title>Writing a System as <m>A\vec{x}=\vec{b}</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The system  
      <m>x + y = 2</m>,  
      <m>2x + y = 4</m>  
      can be written as <m>A\vec{x}=\vec{b}</m>.  
      What is <m>A</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1\\2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The rows contain the coefficients of the system.   
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 4\\1 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the coefficients are incorrect.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that would yield the trivial system <m>x=\vec{b}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vec-mcq-8">
  <title>Dimension of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the dimension of <m>\mathbb{R}^5</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>5</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> consists of all <m>n</m>-tuples of real numbers.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p>4</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—there are five components.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p>10</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this might be confused with combinations; not relevant here.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="linop-definition">
  <statement>
    <p>
      In your own words, describe what a <term>linear operator</term> is.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      A <term>linear operator</term> is a function that takes a vector as input and outputs another
      vector, while preserving the two key properties of linearity:
    </p>
    <me>
      L(\vec{u}+\vec{v}) = L(\vec{u}) + L(\vec{v}), 
      \qquad 
      L(c\vec{u}) = c\,L(\vec{u}),
    </me>
    <p>
      for all vectors <m>\vec{u}, \vec{v}</m> and scalars <m>c</m>.
      If the operator maps a vector space to itself (for example,
      <m>L:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^n</m>), then it is called a linear <em>operator</em>
      rather than just a linear <em>mapping</em>.
      In finite dimensions, these are exactly the operations that can be represented by matrices.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="magnitude-synonym">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Give another word for the <term>magnitude</term> of a vector.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Another common word for the magnitude of a vector is its <em>length</em>.
      In linear algebra, magnitude is also called the <em>norm</em> of the vector.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="basis-error-explanation">
  <statement>
    <p>
      In the text, the author writes the (incorrect) statement:
      <em>“The reason these are called a basis is that every other vector can be written as a linear
      combination of them.”</em>
      Explain precisely what is wrong with this statement, using the correct definitions of
      <term>basis</term>, <term>span</term>, and <term>linear independence</term>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      What the author wrote is only <em>half</em> of the definition of a basis.
      For a set of vectors <m>\{ \vec{v}_1,\dots,\vec{v}_k\}</m> to be a basis for a vector space, two
      things must be true:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Span:</strong> Every vector in the space can be written as a linear combination
        of <m>\vec{v}_1,\dots,\vec{v}_k</m>.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>Linear independence:</strong> No nontrivial linear combination of the vectors
        equals the zero vector.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      The author’s sentence mentions only the spanning property, but not the requirement of linear
      independence.
      Without linear independence, a spanning set is just a <em>spanning set</em>, not a basis.
      For example, in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, the vectors
    </p>

    <me>
      \vec{u}_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix},\qquad
      \vec{u}_2=\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix},\qquad
      \vec{u}_3=\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix},
    </me>

    <p>
      span <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> but are not linearly independent, so they <em>do not</em> form a basis.
      A correct definition requires both spanning and linear independence.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="linmap-vs-matrix">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The textbook says: <em>“Hence, we may think of matrices being linear mappings, and linear
      mappings being matrices.”</em>  
      Then it immediately warns this is not always true.  
      Using the linear operator <m>L(f)=f'</m> on smooth functions, explain why a general linear
      mapping is <em>not</em> always representable by a finite matrix.  
      Extra credit: Describe an infinite-dimensional “matrix” that represents <m>L</m> using Taylor
      series ideas.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      On a finite-dimensional vector space such as <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, every linear mapping can be
      represented by some <m>n\times n</m> matrix.  
      But the mapping <m>L(f)=f'</m> acts on a space of smooth functions, which is
      <em>infinite-dimensional</em>.  
      There is no finite list of basis vectors, so there is no finite matrix that could represent
      <m>L</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Extra credit idea:</strong>  
      If a smooth function <m>f</m> is written as a Taylor series
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} a_k t^k,
    </me>

    <p>
      then
    </p>

    <me>
      f'(t)=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} k\,a_k\,t^{\,k-1}.
    </me>

    <p>
      In the basis <m>\{1, t, t^2, t^3,\dots\}</m>, differentiation is represented by an
      infinite matrix:
    </p>

    <me>
      L \ \leftrightarrow \
      \begin{bmatrix}
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots\\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp \cdots\\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp \cdots\\
      \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This “matrix” is infinite in extent, reflecting the fact that the underlying vector space is
      infinite-dimensional.  
      That is why not all linear mappings are representable by finite matrices.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="parallelogram-rule-labeling">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Label the vectors 
      <m>\vec{u}= \begin{bmatrix}1\\3\end{bmatrix}</m>, 
      <m>\vec{v}= \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>, and 
      <m>\vec{u}+\vec{v}</m> in <xref ref="ParallelogramRule"/>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ParallelogramRule" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>Vectors <m>\vec{u}</m> and <m>\vec{v}</m> (unlabeled for the exercise).</caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <description>
          A 2D coordinate plot showing three arrows from the origin to (1,3), (2,1), and (3,4),
          with light auxiliary segments forming the parallelogram rule construction.
          Axes are labeled <m>x_1</m> (horizontal) and <m>x_2</m> (vertical); ticks 0–4.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    axis lines = middle,
    xmin=0, xmax=4.2, ymin=0, ymax=4.2,
    xtick={0,1,2,3,4}, ytick={0,1,2,3,4},
    tick style={black!60},
    xlabel={$x_1$}, ylabel={$x_2$},
    width=9.2cm, height=7.0cm,
    xlabel style={yshift=0.3em}, ylabel style={yshift=-0.3em}
  ]
    % Unlabeled vectors from the origin:
    \addplot[->, very thick,blue] coordinates {(0,0) (1,3)};  % u
    \addplot[->, very thick,blue] coordinates {(0,0) (2,1)};  % v
    \addplot[->, very thick,blue] coordinates {(0,0) (3,4)};  % u+v

    % Auxiliary edges to illustrate the parallelogram rule:
    \addplot[black!55] coordinates {(1,3) (3,4)};
    \addplot[black!55] coordinates {(2,1) (3,4)};

    % Endpoints as dots:
    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.8pt] coordinates {(1,3) (2,1) (3,4)};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p><strong>Computation.</strong> We have</p>
    <me>
      \vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\3\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
      \vec{v}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
      \vec{u}+\vec{v}=\begin{bmatrix}1+2\\3+1\end{bmatrix}
      =\begin{bmatrix}3\\4\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The sum <m>\vec{u}+\vec{v}</m> is drawn from the origin to <m>(3,4)</m>.
      <xref ref="ParallelogramRule-labeled"/> shows the labels placed along each arrow.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ParallelogramRule-labeled">
      <caption>Labeled vectors <m>\vec{u}</m>, <m>\vec{v}</m>, and <m>\vec{u}+\vec{v}</m>.</caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    axis lines = middle,
    xmin=0, xmax=4.2, ymin=0, ymax=4.2,
    xtick={0,1,2,3,4}, ytick={0,1,2,3,4},
    tick style={black!60},
    xlabel={$x_1$}, ylabel={$x_2$},
    width=9.2cm, height=7.0cm,
    xlabel style={yshift=0.3em}, ylabel style={yshift=-0.3em}
  ]
    % Vectors from the origin:
    \addplot[->, very thick,blue] coordinates {(0,0) (1,3)};  % u
    \addplot[->, very thick,blue] coordinates {(0,0) (2,1)};  % v
    \addplot[->, very thick,blue] coordinates {(0,0) (3,4)};  % u+v

    % Auxiliary edges:
    \addplot[black!55] coordinates {(1,3) (3,4)};
    \addplot[black!55] coordinates {(2,1) (3,4)};

    % Endpoints as dots:
    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.8pt] coordinates {(1,3) (2,1) (3,4)};

    % Labels near the vectors (positions tuned for clarity):
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:0.35,1.85) {\(\vec{u}\)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:1.35,0.62) {\(\vec{v}\)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:2.35,3.05) {\(\vec{u}+\vec{v}\)};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Thus the required labels are:
      <ul>
        <li><m>\vec{u}</m> along the arrow to <m>(1,3)</m>,</li>
        <li><m>\vec{v}</m> along the arrow to <m>(2,1)</m>, and</li>
        <li><m>\vec{u}+\vec{v}</m> along the arrow to <m>(3,4)</m>.</li>
      </ul>
      The faint segments complete the parallelogram rule construction.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vectors-scale-plot">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\displaystyle \vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
      Express (draw) <m>\vec{u}</m>, <m>2\vec{u}</m>, and <m>-\tfrac{3}{2}\vec{u}</m> on the graph in <xref ref="Vectors1"/>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="Vectors1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>Sketch vectors <m>\vec{u}</m>, <m>2\vec{u}</m>, and <m>-\tfrac{3}{2}\vec{u}</m> on this grid.</caption>
      <image width="62%">
        <description>
          A square grid for <m>x_1</m> from −2 to 2 and <m>x_2</m> from −3 to 4 with axes crossing at the origin. 
          Ticks mark each integer; no vectors are drawn here (students add them).
        </description>
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    width=9.2cm, height=9.2cm,
    xmin=-2.2, xmax=2.2, ymin=-3.2, ymax=4.2,
    axis lines=middle,
    xlabel={$x_1$}, ylabel={$x_2$},
    xtick={-2,-1,0,1,2}, ytick={-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3,4},
    tick style={black!70},
    minor x tick num=3, minor y tick num=3,
    grid=both, grid style={black!20}, minor grid style={black!10},
    axis line style={black},
    enlargelimits=false
  ]
    % Empty grid only (students will draw vectors).
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Compute the scaled vectors:
    </p>
    <me>
      \vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
      2\vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\4\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
      -\tfrac{3}{2}\vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}-\tfrac{3}{2}\\-3\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The figure below places arrows from the origin to the endpoints 
      <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,4)</m>, and <m>\bigl(-\tfrac{3}{2},-3\bigr)</m>, and labels each vector.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="Vectors1-labeled">
      <caption>Labeled plot of <m>\vec{u}</m>, <m>2\vec{u}</m>, and <m>-\tfrac{3}{2}\vec{u}</m>.</caption>
      <image width="62%">
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    width=9.2cm, height=9.2cm,
    xmin=-2.2, xmax=2.2, ymin=-3.2, ymax=4.2,
    axis lines=middle,
    xlabel={$x_1$}, ylabel={$x_2$},
    xtick={-2,-1,0,1,2}, ytick={-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3,4},
    tick style={black!70},
    minor x tick num=3, minor y tick num=3,
    grid=both, grid style={black!20}, minor grid style={black!10},
    axis line style={black},
    enlargelimits=false
  ]
    % --- vectors from the origin ---
    % u = (1,2)
    \addplot[->, very thick, color=blue] coordinates {(0,0) (1,2)};
    % 2u = (2,4)
    \addplot[->, very thick, color=teal!70!black] coordinates {(0,0) (2,4)};
    % -3/2 u = (-1.5, -3)
    \addplot[->, very thick, color=red!80!black] coordinates {(0,0) (-1.5,-3)};

    % endpoints as filled dots
    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.8pt, color=blue] coordinates {(1,2)};
    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.8pt, color=teal!70!black] coordinates {(2,4)};
    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1.8pt, color=red!80!black] coordinates {(-1.5,-3)};

    % labels placed near each arrow
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:0.6,1.2) {\(\vec{u}\)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:1.3,3.0) {\(2\vec{u}\)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:-1.4,-1.7) {\(-\tfrac{3}{2}\vec{u}\)};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Hence the three vectors are correctly drawn to the points  
      <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,4)</m>, and <m>\bigl(-\tfrac{3}{2},-3\bigr)</m>, respectively.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vectors2-linear-combinations">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let 
      <m>\displaystyle \vec{v}_{1}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}</m> 
      and 
      <m>\displaystyle \vec{v}_{2}=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\2\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
      Express each of the following vectors as a linear combination of 
      <m>\vec{v}_{1}</m> and <m>\vec{v}_{2}</m>.  
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="Vectors2">
      <caption>An interesting grid for plotting vectors.</caption>
      <image width="75%">
        <description>
          A coordinate plane on x1,x2 from -8 to 8.  
          The grid consists of evenly spaced parallel lines in two directions:
          one set with slope 1/2 (parallel to v1) and one set with slope -1 (parallel to v2).
        </description>
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    width=14cm, height=10.5cm,
    xmin=-8.5, xmax=8.5, ymin=-8.5, ymax=8.5,
    axis lines=middle,
    xlabel={$x_1$}, ylabel={$x_2$},
    xtick={-8,-6,-4,-2,0,2,4,6,8},
    ytick={-8,-6,-4,-2,0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8},
    tick style={black}
  ]

    % --- parallel lines to v1 (direction  (2,1)  slope = 1/2 ) ---
    \foreach \c in {-16,-14,...,16} {
      \addplot[black!40, thin, domain=-12:12] ({x}, {0.5*x + \c});
    }

    % --- parallel lines to v2 (direction (-2,2) slope = -1 ) ---
    \foreach \c in {-16,-14,...,16} {
      \addplot[black!40, thin, domain=-12:12] ({x}, {-x + \c});
    }

  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <ol>
      <li><p><m>\vec{a}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
      <li><p><m>\vec{b}=\begin{bmatrix}-4\\1\end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
      <li><p><m>\vec{c}=\begin{bmatrix}6\\6\end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p>We solve for scalars <m>\alpha,\beta</m> such that:</p>

    <me>
      \alpha\vec{v}_{1}+\beta\vec{v}_{2}
      =
      \alpha\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}
      +\beta\begin{bmatrix}-2\\2\end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}2\alpha - 2\beta \\ \alpha + 2\beta\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <!-- ======================================================== -->
    <!-- 1. Solve for a = [0; 3]                                  -->
    <!-- ======================================================== -->

    <p><strong>1) For <m>\vec{a}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}</m></strong></p>

    <me>
      2\alpha - 2\beta = 0,\qquad \alpha + 2\beta = 3.
    </me>

    <p>
      From the first equation <m>\alpha=\beta</m>.  
      Substitute:
    </p>

    <me>
      \alpha + 2\alpha = 3 \Rightarrow 3\alpha = 3 \Rightarrow \alpha = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus <m>\beta=1</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \boxed{\vec{a} = \vec{v}_{1} + \vec{v}_{2}}.
    </me>

    <!-- ======================================================== -->
    <!-- 2. Solve for b = [-4; 1]                                 -->
    <!-- ======================================================== -->

    <p><strong>2) For <m>\vec{b}=\begin{bmatrix}-4\\1\end{bmatrix}</m></strong></p>

    <me>
      2\alpha - 2\beta = -4,\qquad \alpha + 2\beta = 1.
    </me>

    <p>Divide first eqn by 2: <m>\alpha - \beta = -2</m>.</p>

    <me>
      \alpha - \beta = -2,\qquad \alpha + 2\beta = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Subtract the first from the second:
      <m>3\beta = 3</m> so <m>\beta=1</m>.  
      Then <m>\alpha - 1 = -2</m>, so <m>\alpha=-1</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \boxed{\vec{b} = -\vec{v}_{1} + \vec{v}_{2}}.
    </me>

    <!-- ======================================================== -->
    <!-- 3. Solve for c = [6; 6]                                  -->
    <!-- ======================================================== -->

    <p><strong>3) For <m>\vec{c}=\begin{bmatrix}6\\6\end{bmatrix}</m></strong></p>

    <me>
      2\alpha - 2\beta = 6,\qquad \alpha + 2\beta = 6.
    </me>

    <p>
      Divide first eqn: <m>\alpha - \beta = 3</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \alpha - \beta = 3,\qquad \alpha + 2\beta = 6.
    </me>

    <p>
      Subtract:
      <m>3\beta = 3</m> → <m>\beta=1</m>.  
      Then <m>\alpha - 1 = 3</m> → <m>\alpha=4</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \boxed{\vec{c} = 4\vec{v}_{1} + \vec{v}_{2}}.
    </me>

    <!-- ======================================================== -->
    <!-- GRAPHICAL SOLUTION PLOT -->
    <!-- ======================================================== -->

    <p>The following plot shows the three vectors placed on the same lattice:</p>

    <figure xml:id="Vectors2-labeled">
      <caption>Vectors <m>\vec{a},\vec{b},\vec{c}</m> expressed in the basis <m>\{\vec{v}_1,\vec{v}_2\}</m>.</caption>
      <image width="75%">
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    width=14cm, height=10.5cm,
    xmin=-8.5, xmax=8.5, ymin=-8.5, ymax=8.5,
    axis lines=middle,
    xlabel={$x_1$}, ylabel={$x_2$},
    xtick={-8,-6,-4,-2,0,2,4,6,8},
    ytick={-8,-6,-4,-2,0,2,4,6,8},
    tick style={black}
  ]

    % --- slanted grid: parallel to v1 and v2 ---
    \foreach \c in {-16,-14,...,16} {
      \addplot[black!35, thin, domain=-12:12] ({x}, {0.5*x + \c});
      \addplot[black!35, thin, domain=-12:12] ({x}, {-x + \c});
    }

    % --- vectors ---
    % a = v1 + v2 = (0,3)
    \addplot[->, very thick, color=blue] coordinates {(0,0) (0,3)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:0.3,1.7) {$\vec{a}$};

    % b = -v1 + v2 = (-4,1)
    \addplot[->, very thick, color=red] coordinates {(0,0) (-4,1)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:-2.3,0.6) {$\vec{b}$};

    % c = 4v1 + v2 = (6,6)
    \addplot[->, very thick, color=green!60!black] coordinates {(0,0) (6,6)};
    \node[fill=white, inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:3.7,3.2) {$\vec{c}$};

  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matrix-from-images-of-basis">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose a linear mapping <m>F:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{3}</m> takes 
      <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(1,2,3)</m> and takes <m>(0,1)</m> to <m>(4,5,6)</m>. 
      Write down the matrix representing <m>F</m> (with respect to the standard bases).
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      In the standard bases, the matrix of a linear map has as its columns the images of the standard
      basis vectors <m>\vec e_1=(1,0)</m> and <m>\vec e_2=(0,1)</m>. Therefore,
    </p>
    <me>
      F(\vec e_1) = \begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}, 
      \qquad 
      F(\vec e_2) = \begin{bmatrix}4\\5\\6\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Hence the matrix of <m>F</m> (with respect to the standard bases of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and 
      <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>) is
    </p>
    <me>
      [F] \;=\;
      \begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp 4\\
        2 \amp 5\\
        3 \amp 6
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives41">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
     Analyze how linear mappings transform vectors and how these mappings can be represented using matrices.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Apply matrix methods to organize and simplify large systems, including those arising from differential equations. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Develop geometric and algebraic intuition for high‑dimensional vector spaces and the role of 
      linear structure in modeling real‑world problems.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>